<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-756-356  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 756 356.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 13 1990 v24 n33 pS18(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Desktop deprivation. (microcomputers in Japan; includes relatedarticles on revving up business with microcomputers and customizedtemplates)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gillin, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The usage of the microcomputer in Japanese industry has grown farslower than in the US because of language, lack of office space,culture, incompatible standards, limited software and high costs.andO;The Japanese language has complex characters and even the leadingJapanese word processing software, which takes about 150Kbytes ofmemory overhead, requires that users enter words phoneticallyfirst before a front-end processor interprets the phonetic inputand translates it into a displayed text.andP;  The high cost of officespace, the cultural de-emphasis of data, a wide array ofincompatible microcomputer standards, limited software packagesand the high cost of machines has also contributed to a limiteduse of microcomputers in Japan.andP;  Only about two percent of thepopulation makes use of microcomputers, as opposed to 10 percentof the US population.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     JapanMicrocomputersTrendsMarket AnalysisSocial IssuesComputer industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   Slow bloom (microcomputer installed base Japan vs. US). (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>